title: SpeechJammer: A System Utilizing Artificial Speech Disturbance with Delayed Auditory Feedback
title_en: SpeechJammer: A System Utilizing Artificial Speech Disturbance with Delayed Auditory Feedback
abstract: 本研究は遅延聴覚フィードバックを用いて話者の発話を人工的に妨害するシステムを提案している。提案システムは話者の音声を取得して遅延を付与して再生する構成であり，遅延の固定化や時間変動化，および距離に応じた遅延補正を取り入れて実装性を検討している。
abstract_en: This work proposes a system that artificially disturbs a speaker's speech using delayed auditory feedback. The proposed system captures a speaker's voice, applies configurable fixed or time-varying delays, and incorporates distance-based delay compensation to evaluate practical implementation.
positioning_summary: 本研究は遅延聴覚フィードバック（DAF）を用いた発話妨害の技術領域を扱っている。本文献は放送や会議などの場面で不要な発話を制御する課題として発話妨害を位置づけており，公共空間や配信での応用可能性を議論している。
positioning_summary_en: This study addresses the technical domain of speech disturbance using delayed auditory feedback (DAF). The paper positions speech disturbance as a control problem relevant to situations such as broadcasting and meetings and discusses applicability to public spaces and streaming.
purpose_summary: 本研究の目的は遅延聴覚フィードバックを応用して話者の発話を効果的に妨害する実用的な手段を構築することである。研究は不要な長話や一方的発言を抑制することを対象とし，現場で他者の発話を乱す実用化を目指している。
purpose_summary_en: The purpose of this work is to construct a practical means to disturb a speaker's speech using delayed auditory feedback. The work targets suppression of unwanted long monologues and one-sided speech and aims for practical deployment to disrupt others' speech in real environments.
method_summary: 本研究は話者の音声をマイクで取得して遅延処理後に再生する遅延聴覚フィードバックベースの装置を設計している。提案手法はPC上の信号処理環境とマイクロコントローラ＋専用回路による低遅延実装を組み合わせ，固定遅延や時間変動遅延（例: D=0.15+0.05·sin(2πT)）や距離補正式 D = D_daf + 2x/v を用いる方式である。
method_summary_en: This study designs a device based on delayed auditory feedback that captures a speaker's voice with a microphone and replays it after delay processing. The proposed method combines a PC-based signal processing environment with a microcontroller and dedicated circuitry for low-latency implementation, supports fixed and time-varying delays (e.g., D=0.15+0.05·sin(2πT)), and applies distance compensation using D = D_daf + 2x/v.
evaluation_summary: 本研究はシステム遅延の実測と屋内外での実験やオンラインデモによる観察を用いて評価を行っている。評価では文献で報告されるDAFの有効範囲0.004–0.195秒や実装上の処理遅延約9.2 ms–192 msといった定量値や室温20°Cで最大約34 mまでの距離検討を示し，評価は主に測定値とデモ観察に基づいているが正式な被験者を用いた定量的ユーザースタディは行われていない。
evaluation_summary_en: The evaluation used measured system latencies, indoor and outdoor experiments, and online demo observations. The evaluation reported quantitative figures such as reported effective DAF ranges of 0.004–0.195 s, implementation processing delays approximately 9.2 ms–192 ms, and tests up to about 34 m at 20°C, and the evaluation was mainly based on measurements and demos without a formal quantitative user study.

Title: SpeechJammer: A System Utilizing Artificial Speech Disturbance with Delayed Auditory Feedback
Authors: Kazutaka Kurihara, Koji Tsukada
Year: 2010
Abstract: This work proposes a system that artificially disturbs a speaker's speech using delayed auditory feedback. The proposed system captures a speaker's voice, applies configurable fixed or time-varying delays, and incorporates distance-based delay compensation to evaluate practical implementation.
Positioning Summary: This study addresses the technical domain of speech disturbance using delayed auditory feedback (DAF). The paper positions speech disturbance as a control problem relevant to situations such as broadcasting and meetings and discusses applicability to public spaces and streaming.
Purpose Summary: The purpose of this work is to construct a practical means to disturb a speaker's speech using delayed auditory feedback. The work targets suppression of unwanted long monologues and one-sided speech and aims for practical deployment to disrupt others' speech in real environments.
Method Summary: This study designs a device based on delayed auditory feedback that captures a speaker's voice with a microphone and replays it after delay processing. The proposed method combines a PC-based signal processing environment with a microcontroller and dedicated circuitry for low-latency implementation, supports fixed and time-varying delays (e.g., D=0.15+0.05·sin(2πT)), and applies distance compensation using D = D_daf + 2x/v.
Evaluation Summary: The evaluation used measured system latencies, indoor and outdoor experiments, and online demo observations. The evaluation reported quantitative figures such as reported effective DAF ranges of 0.004–0.195 s, implementation processing delays approximately 9.2 ms–192 ms, and tests up to about 34 m at 20°C, and the evaluation was mainly based on measurements and demos without a formal quantitative user study.
